<TR BACKGROUND="" BGCOLOR="#000000"><TD COLSPAN=3><TABLE WIDTH=100% CELLSPACING=0 CELLPADDING=0><TR><TD WIDTH=200 ALIGN="LEFT">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;<a href="/cgi-bin/advent.pl?day=14&show_all=1"><font size=2>&lt;&lt;&lt;&nbsp;DEC&nbsp;14</font></a></TD><TD WIDTH=200 ALIGN="CENTER"><a href="/cgi-bin/advent.pl"><font size=2>HOME</font></a></TD><TD ALIGN="CENTER"><a class="addthis_button" href="http://www.addthis.com/bookmark.php?v=250&amp;pub=xa-4b157e7f1b908808"><img src="http://s7.addthis.com/static/btn/v2/lg-share-en.gif" width="125" height="16" alt="Bookmark and Share" style="border:0"/></a><script type="text/javascript" src="http://s7.addthis.com/js/250/addthis_widget.js#pub=xa-4b157e7f1b908808"></script></TD><TD WIDTH=200 ALIGN="RIGHT"><a href="/cgi-bin/advent.pl?day=16&show_all=1"><font size=2>DEC&nbsp;16&nbsp;&gt;&gt;&gt;</font></a>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;</TD></TR></TABLE></TD></TR>
<TR HEIGHT=5><TD COLSPAN=3 BACKGROUND="" BGCOLOR="#000000"></TD></TR>
<TR><TD WIDTH=5 BACKGROUND="" BGCOLOR="#000000"></TD>
<TD BACKGROUND="/black6.png">
<TABLE CELLPADDING=5><TR><TD>
	<TABLE WIDTH=100% CELLSPACING=0 CELLPADDING=0><TR><TD>
<IMG ALIGN=RIGHT WIDTH=130 HEIGHT=130 SRC="chocs/choc_day_15.png" ALT="chocolate"><IMG ALIGN=LEFT WIDTH=200 HEIGHT=190 SRC="globes/advent_globe_15.png" ALT="snowglobe"><table cellpadding=10 align="center" background="/black4.png" width=430><TR><TD><center><font size=6 color="#ffff00"><b><i>SPACE HARRIER</i></b></font><br><font size=3 color="red"><b><i>10 days to Christmas</i></b></font></center></TD></TR></TABLE><p>
This was the biggie that magazines were excited about in the run-up to
Christmas 1986. The arcade version was a slick into-the-screen 3D
blaster with the novel hook of having a sit-in version which used to
swing a little to the left and right as you moved the joystick. The
graphics were bright and colourful and the action was very hectic
indeed with plenty of blasting and dodging. The technology had got to
the stage where the idea of the "impossible to convert" game had
started entering to vocabulary of gaming journalists, and it was this
"impossibility" which excited the readers.
<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;<TABLE ALIGN="left" WIDTH=279 CELLPADDING=5><TR>
<TD><a href="pngs/d15_1986_pre5.png" target="1986_pre5.png"><IMG SRC="pngs/d15_1986_pre5_small.jpg" WIDTH=279 HEIGHT=200></a></TD></TR>
<TR><TD COLSPAN=1 ALIGN="CENTER"><font size=-1 color="yellow"><b><i>YS's Art Dept were starting to fire up their paint brushes by this point.</i></b></font></TD></TR>
</TABLE><TABLE CELLPADDING=10 ALIGN="right"><TR><TD><TABLE WIDTH=222 ALIGN="CENTER" VALIGN="MIDDLE" BGCOLOR="#000000" BACKGROUND=""><TR><TD><center><object width="212" height="172"><param name="movie" value="http://www.youtube.com/v/yosuvf7Unmg&hl=en_GB&fs=1&"></param><param name="allowFullScreen" value="true"></param><param name="allowscriptaccess" value="always"></param><embed src="http://www.youtube.com/v/yosuvf7Unmg&hl=en_GB&fs=1&" type="application/x-shockwave-flash" allowscriptaccess="always" allowfullscreen="true" width="212" height="172"></embed></object><br>
<FONT size=-1 COLOR="#FFFF00"><b><u>Back To The Future Trailer</u></b></font></center><font size=-1 color="#ffffff">"...out of a <i>DeLorean</i>??!" <b><i>(1:46)</i></b></font><center><font size=-2 color="#ffffff"><i>Watch full-sized <a href="http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=yosuvf7Unmg" target="yosuvf7Unmg">at YouTube</a></font></center></TD></TR></TABLE><br></TD></TR></TABLE>
Bizarrely, converters Elite didn't do much to hype up the game even
though it was a triple-A Christmas title, only advertising it in Crash
magazine for a few months, and even then most of the time the game
shared its billing with lesser titles such as the over-hyped <i>Scooby
Doo</i>, which is odd considering that 1986 was a golden year for Elite
mainly due to their arcade conversions such as <i>Bomb Jack</i> and <i>Paperboy</i>. Maybe after all of their investment in the hastily-rewritten <i>Scooby
Doo</i> meant that they had to put most of their eggs in that basket in
order to try and recoup their costs.
<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;You could see the early germination of the magazine hype machine in
the previews for this game. Crash had a half-page of breathless
commentary, whilst Your Sinclair went for the two-page artwork-backed
MegaPreview format which they had been developing all through 1986,
together with magazine cover artwork. C&VG skipped the preview stage
and went straight for a double-page spread with programmer interview,
reviews, and simple artwork backed by a very sharp illustration on the
cover.
<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;<TABLE ALIGN="right" WIDTH=292 CELLPADDING=5><TR>
<TD><a href="pngs/d15_1986_cov2.png" target="1986_cov2.png"><IMG SRC="pngs/d15_1986_cov2_small.jpg" WIDTH=142 HEIGHT=200></a></TD><TD>&nbsp;&nbsp;</TD><TD><a href="pngs/d15_1986_cov4.png" target="1986_cov4.png"><IMG SRC="pngs/d15_1986_cov4_small.jpg" WIDTH=140 HEIGHT=200></a></TD></TR>
<TR><TD COLSPAN=3 ALIGN="CENTER"><font size=-1 color="yellow"><b><i>It may have been a simple game, but it was a blockbuster which deserved hype.</i></b></font></TD></TR>
</TABLE>Sinclair User accidentally revealed part of its shortcomings by being
exposed by C&VG for reviewing a preview copy of the game, such were
the pressures at the time of being the first magazine to review a
game. It was those sorts of shenanigans that YS would openly act
against, providing a "seal of approval" to its own reviews
guaranteeing that all reviews are made purely with finished copies of
the games, even if it meant being scooped by other magazines.
<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;<TABLE CELLPADDING=10 ALIGN="left"><TR><TD><TABLE WIDTH=222 ALIGN="CENTER" VALIGN="MIDDLE" BGCOLOR="#000000" BACKGROUND=""><TR><TD><center><object width="212" height="172"><param name="movie" value="http://www.youtube.com/v/zX1CuOHIRAQ&hl=en_GB&fs=1&"></param><param name="allowFullScreen" value="true"></param><param name="allowscriptaccess" value="always"></param><embed src="http://www.youtube.com/v/zX1CuOHIRAQ&hl=en_GB&fs=1&" type="application/x-shockwave-flash" allowscriptaccess="always" allowfullscreen="true" width="212" height="172"></embed></object><br>
<FONT size=-1 COLOR="#FFFF00"><b><u>Thames Trailer for Boxing Day 1984</u></b></font></center><font size=-1 color="#ffffff">Strangely familiar to a lot of line ups on ITV in later years! <b><i>(0:59)</i></b></font><center><font size=-2 color="#ffffff"><i>Watch full-sized <a href="http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=zX1CuOHIRAQ" target="zX1CuOHIRAQ">at YouTube</a></font></center></TD></TR></TABLE><br></TD></TR></TABLE>
The final reviews were generally positive, with the game well up to
the standards of the time. However it suffered from "<i>Commando</i>
syndrome" - it was a very efficient conversion of a new game format
with several shiny new programming tricks in order to keep the speed
and excitement up. But... the game format was a very simple one of
dodging and blasting, and once the novelty wore off the very basic
gameplay shone through. So whilst the original review ratings were
around the 90% mark, come its re-release that had dropped to 70% and
below, and it's really difficult to argue against that. When I bought
it on its re-release I remember feeling disappointed how shallow the
gameplay was, and the graphics, whilst good for 1986, seemed rather
muddled a few years on.
<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;</TD></TR><TR><TD><IMG SRC="chocs/voxpop.png" ALIGN="LEFT"><br><IMG SRC="pngs/jmk.png" ALIGN="RIGHT"><TABLE BACKGROUND="/black7.png"><TR><TD><FONT SIZE=5 COLOR="#ffff00"><B><I>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;JAMES MCKAY&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;</I></B></FONT></TD></TR></TABLE><br>
<b>James wrote the influential X128 Spectrum emulator which was one of <i>the</i> emulators to use at one time. James?</b><br><br><b><i><font color="#ff3030">Who are you and what are you up to?</font></i></b><br>
I am James McKay, ex-author of x128 and games programmer / drifter.  I am perpetually working on <i>KO99</i> <i>(Klass Of '99 - a very good remake based on the Skool Daze games --NickH)</i> for the Spectrum (which runs, but is dead slow), leaving the windows version of x128 in an unfinished state and writing the odd Tandy game.  I've done a few GBA/DS games for the money.
<br><b><i><font color="#ff3030">Favourite cracker gift (aside from fortune-telling fish, naturally)?<TABLE ALIGN="left" WIDTH=134 CELLPADDING=5><TR>
<TD><a href="pngs/d15_1986_pre1.png" target="1986_pre1.png"><IMG SRC="pngs/d15_1986_pre1_small.jpg" WIDTH=134 HEIGHT=200></a></TD></TR>
<TR><TD COLSPAN=1 ALIGN="CENTER"><font size=-1 color="yellow"><b><i>Crash didn't really have the hang of hyping, but the half-page splash was exciting.</i></b></font></TD></TR>
</TABLE></font></i></b><br>
They're not very good are they?  I think I once had a little plastic car that could be assembled.  It would be better if they put sweets in them instead of paper, gunpowder and a bit of plastic.
<br><b><i><font color="#ff3030">Favourite Christmas Song?</font></i></b><br>
Burn them, burn them all!  ;)
<br><b><i><font color="#ff3030">Best memory of Christmases gone by?<TABLE CELLPADDING=10 ALIGN="right"><TR><TD><TABLE WIDTH=222 ALIGN="CENTER" VALIGN="MIDDLE" BGCOLOR="#000000" BACKGROUND=""><TR><TD><center><object width="212" height="172"><param name="movie" value="http://www.youtube.com/v/aOsqWGiSFzM&hl=en_GB&fs=1&"></param><param name="allowFullScreen" value="true"></param><param name="allowscriptaccess" value="always"></param><embed src="http://www.youtube.com/v/aOsqWGiSFzM&hl=en_GB&fs=1&" type="application/x-shockwave-flash" allowscriptaccess="always" allowfullscreen="true" width="212" height="172"></embed></object><br>
<FONT size=-1 COLOR="#FFFF00"><b><u>1983 ads from Channel Four</u></b></font></center><font size=-1 color="#ffffff">We're used to a lot of razzmatazz in Christmas logos now, but in 1983 Channel Four went a bit, well, minimalist. Very '80s. <b><i>(2:52)</i></b></font><center><font size=-2 color="#ffffff"><i>Watch full-sized <a href="http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=aOsqWGiSFzM" target="aOsqWGiSFzM">at YouTube</a></font></center></TD></TR></TABLE><br></TD></TR></TABLE>
</font></i></b><br>
One time I was on a cruise ship which capsized and we had to scramble up to the hull before we were all killed by a series of despicable cliches.  Oh, no, wait... that was <i>The Poseidon Adventure</i>.
<br><b><i><font color="#ff3030">Best Speccy Christmas memory?</font></i></b><br>
I remember sleeping on the couch so that I could play my new games early (and on the big telly) before anyone else came downstairs.  I got up at 6-ish, watched a cartoon (Ziggy's gift) and then was impressed by the <i>Technician Ted</i> 128 loader.  I got <i>Renegade</i> as well as some others, so it might've been 1987.
<br><b><i><font color="#ff3030">Favourite Quality Street chocolate?</font></i></b><br>
Hmm... the purple one.  Nothing beats a Guylian shell though.
<br><b><i><font color="#ff3030">Best present ever?</font></i></b><br>
An orange stuffed full of socks.
<br><b><i><font color="#ff3030">Speccy game you most looked forward to?</font></i></b><br>
Probably <i>Gauntlet</i> and I loved it.  It met my expectations, compared to stuff I looked forward to like <i>Indiana Jones and The Temple of Doom</i>... urg.
</TD></TR>
</TABLE><p>
</TD></TR></TABLE>
